\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 Paul Kuehneman
\f0\b0 \cb1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\i \cb2 Interim Chief Financial Officer & Controller
\f0\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 This is Paul. So on the segment detailed guide, all in for fiscal '26, we expect Retail to have modest declines in volume with low single-digit increases in net sales. Foodservice will have low single-digit increases in volume with net sales in the mid-single digits. And then International also expecting low single-digit increases in volume with high single-digit increases in net sales. And as Jeff has stated, segment profit growth by all 3 segments for the course of the year.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 Leah Jordan
\f0\b0 \cb1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\i \cb2 Goldman Sachs Group, Inc., Research Division
\f0\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 Okay. Great. And then maybe just some comments around the competitive overall across your categories in Retail. I mean what are you seeing from peers as you start to put through some targeted pricing in some areas? And then -- but you're also kind of planning for incremental brand investments as well. So just the competitive environment overall.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 John Ghingo
\f0\b0 \cb1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\i \cb2 President & Director
\f0\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 Yes, sure. I can take that. This is John. From a Retail perspective, we do feel very good about the top line momentum we're seeing across the Retail business despite what is a choppy and competitive environment and that strained consumer backdrop. When you look at the drivers underneath that consumption performance, you can see in the scanner data, our flagship and rising brands continue to perform well. In the latest 13 weeks, they were up 3.7% versus last year. That carried our total Hormel portfolio to over 1% consumption growth in the latest 13 weeks.\cb1 \
\cb2 Some of the standout performers, Jennie-O ground turkey, where we're up double digits, we're certainly pacing ahead of the competition. Planters back to double-digit growth, also pacing ahead of the competition. We're seeing good strong growth in our rising Mexican brands, Wholly Guacamole and Herdez grew 7% and 5%, respectively. Applegate continues to grow. So we like our portfolio. We like the momentum we have on Retail.\cb1 \
\cb2 We have taken, as we've talked about, multiple waves of pricing action. We -- in the last quarter call, we talked about that we had announced a wave of pricing, that we were going to monitor if we needed additional pricing. As we got deeper into the quarter and saw the markets continue to rise, we did, in fact, announce another wave of pricing, which largely will benefit us in the second quarter.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 To your point around how do we maintain that momentum, how do we feel competitively, we're going to continue to invest in our brands. We're going to continue to invest behind our core brands as well as our innovation to weather that competitively. And all in all, we certainly see competitive activity in some of the categories that is aggressive, but we feel like we have good, differentiated positions. We know where our growth is needed to come from, and we're going to continue to invest in those spots.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 Operator
\f0\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 Your next question comes from the line of Max Gumport from BNP Paribas.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 Max Andrew Gumport
\f0\b0 \cb1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\i \cb2 BNP Paribas, Research Division
\f0\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 I was hoping for an update on tariffs, particularly if there are any expenses, particularly such as those associated with cashews that you incurred in FY '25 that might not repeat in FY '26 due to recent exemptions? And then if so, if you could quantify that impact for us?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 Paul Kuehneman
\f0\b0 \cb1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\i \cb2 Interim Chief Financial Officer & Controller
\f0\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 Yes, Max, this is Paul. Thanks for the question. Overall, a message on tariffs. Really, we feel that we're fairly insulated. Obviously, the global environment remains dynamic and it's ever changing. For '26, the range that we think that we'll have on tariffs is $25 million to $35 million, and it's mainly related to supplies in steel and aluminum.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 Obviously, we were watching cashews until the recent announcements of the removal of reciprocal tariffs. We haven't really quantified that exact amount that we had in '25 to give you a range on the '26 question.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 Max Andrew Gumport
\f0\b0 \cb1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\i \cb2 BNP Paribas, Research Division
\f0\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 Okay. I think that $25 million to $35 million, is that roughly in line with the total tariffs that you saw on your P&L in '25 then? I think you had quantified a $0.01 to $0.02 impact, I believe, in the second half of '25.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 Paul Kuehneman
\f0\b0 \cb1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\i \cb2 Interim Chief Financial Officer & Controller
\f0\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 Yes. So on a full year basis, that is correct.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 Max Andrew Gumport
\f0\b0 \cb1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\i \cb2 BNP Paribas, Research Division
\f0\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 Okay. Great. Then that takes me to my second question, which would be -- I mean I still think there's plenty of discrete items you have in fiscal year '26, that will be a help to your profit growth. So you've mentioned admin savings. I think you said it was 2 to 3x the cost to implement, which I think is $20 million to $25 million the cost to implement, but correct me if that's wrong. But if that's right, that would be, maybe at the midpoint, roughly $60 million in savings, not all of that is going to flow to the bottom line. Some of it gets invested, but let's assume half flows to the bottom line, that's $30 million in profit growth. You've got the chicken recalls that you're lapping, the fire at the Little Rock facility that you're lapping. So that's another $20 million or so in profit growth. So now we're at $50 million of profit growth. Your guidance is for $40 million to $100 million. And you've also got a benefit coming from T&M, again, some of which gets reinvested, but some of which flows to the bottom line and then whole bird turkey pricing.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 So I was hoping just to get a bit more color on sort of what's -- what am I missing? What's dragging you down? Is it other forms of inflation like on beef and nuts? Just one -- just given these discrete factors, I'm trying to get a better sense for what might be holding you back and sort of keeping the low end of the range at 4% EBIT growth.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 Jeffrey Ettinger
\f0\b0 \cb1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\i \cb2 Interim CEO & Director
\f0\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 All right. I'll start, Max, this is Jeff. I mean -- you're correct that the $20 million to $25 million number in terms of the onetime cost is what we've reported. And so your math of the 2 to 3x works in that regard. And you correctly pointed out that, that ends up being the total available savings, but then we are going to be reinvesting parts of it in certain areas.\cb1 \
\cb2 I think a couple of other factors that we probably could point out to you that might mitigate your math a little bit. One, I'll remind you again about Q1. So we start out the year in somewhat of a hole. So the implied rest of the year is quite a bit higher than 7% then. And so that does factor in some of the advantages that you're citing.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 Secondly, I mean, I think the other thing that maybe models miss that we've talked about in the past is in the pricing area that while we're in a reasonably good position to be current to the cost on the Foodservice side with some lag, in Retail, it's a more complex decision, and there are cases where, okay, if we're -- yes, the costs are up this much, but if we price to that same equivalent amount, it's going to really harm the long-term future of the brand. There are times where we've chosen not to do that. And so some of the math factoring into how we think '26 plays out has that factored in as well.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 Operator
\f0\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 Your next question comes from the line of Rupesh Parikh from Oppenheimer.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
